      "alt": "Claude conversation, prompt and response\n\n> Does this insight accord well with any established theory?\n\nYes - quite well, and in a way that sharpens the thread.\nThe closest fit is reflexive/recursive belief hierarchies from game theory and epistemic logic. Your \"X as seen by Y\" is exactly an epistemic operator Ky (X), and \"B as seen by C'as seen by A\" is KaKc(B). The infinite tower of nested operators is the standard construction of interactive belief hierarchies (Harsanyi types, formalized by Mertens-Zamir, Brandenburger-Dekel). Your instinct that the set shouldn't be \"closed by fiat\" is correct in the strongest possible way: the full type space is necessarily infinite, and the technical achievement of that literature was showing a universal type space exists that closes the regress without truncation.",
